#1

The dimensions of the 2002 dataset are 15976 observations (rows) by 22 variables (columns). Checking the headers and footers of the 2002 dataset reveal that there are no obvious issues, such as improbable values or NAs. It also reveals that the dataset appears to be in chronological order by data and Site ID. Checking the names of the variables reveals that our variable of interest is called âDaily Mean PM2.5 Concentration.â Checking the variable types in the 2002 dataset reveals that our variable of interest is a double (continuous) variable. The distribution of the âDaily Mean PM2.5 Concentrationâ variable is not normal; it is right skewed. Aside from this, there are no obvious outliers or improbable values, such as extremely negative values.

The dimensions of the 2022 dataset are 59918 observations by 22 variables. Checking the headers, footers, variable names, and variable types reveals the same information that was found for the 2002 dataset. The distribution of the âDaily Mean PM2.5 Concentrationâ is more-or-less normally distributed, however there appears to be an outlier somewhere around PM2.5=300 (confirmed with max() function).

# combined dataset
epa_all <- bind_rows(epa2002, epa2022)

# rename variables
epa_all <-
  epa_all %>%
  rename(concentration = `Daily Mean PM2.5 Concentration`,
         lon = `Site Longitude`,
         lat = `Site Latitude`)

# create year variable
epa_all <-
  epa_all %>%
  mutate(year = factor(year(mdy(Date))))

#3

The monitoring sites seem to be distributed near areas that have big towns and cities. There are many along the coast, especially near the SF Bay and LA, and in the central valley. There are none in the Mojave Desert. The distribution looks roughly the same between 2002 and 2022, except that there is increased density of the sites seen in the 2022 map.

us_map <- map_data("state", region = "california")

               color = "white") +
  geom_point(data = epa_all, mapping = aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = year)) +
  facet_wrap(~ year, nrow = 1)

#4

After running hist() and summary() on the PM2.5 data in the combined dataset, it looks like there are no missing values or NAs, but it does appear that there are some negative values. These would be considered implausible since particulate concentration cannot physically be less than 0. I calculated the proportions to find that there were no (0%) implausible values in the 2002 dataset, while there were 3.59% implausible values in the 2022 dataset. There appears to be an outlier at PM2.5=302.50um/m3. I called these âtoo largeâ and decided to calculate their proportions in the 2002 and 2022 datasets to potentially assist with visualization later, even though these are not necessarily erroneous or implausible. I found that the 2002 dataset had 0.0125% large values, and the 2022 dataset was 0.0618% large values. Overall, it appears that the 2022 dataset has a larger proportion of implausible and âtoo largeâ values than the 2002 dataset.

#5

To understand how PM2.5 concentrations changed between 2002 and 2022 at the state level, I created boxplots to show the distribution of PM2.5 concentration in both years. I filtered the data to only include rows that reported a PM2.5 concentrations of 100um/m3 or less aid with visualizing the distributions, since these values made it so that the âboxâ portion of the boxplot was difficult to see, and in #4 we saw that these values make up a very small fraction of the total data. The boxplots and summary stats show that there is a clear reduction in PM2.5 concentrations between 2002 and 2022, with means of 16.12um/m3 and 8.42um/m3, respectively. I also found that the 2022 concentrations were more condensed than the 2002 concentrations, with the exception of outliers. Within each year, I also averaged the PM2.5 concentrations for each month and plotted these in order to see whether the PM2.5 concentrations are reduced throughout the entire year of 2022, or if instead there was a month of peaked concentration. The plot shows that the PM2.5 concentrations in 2022 were reduced throughout all 12 months compared to 2002.

# statewide resolution

  labs(title = "Statewide Concentrations of PM2.5 in 2002 and 2022", 
       x = "year",
       y = "PM2.5 Concentration")

epa_avg <- 
  epa_all %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(mdy(Date), label = F)) %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarize(avg_conc = mean(concentration), .groups = "drop")

epa_avg %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = month, y = avg_conc, color = year)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = month, y = avg_conc, color = year)) +
  labs(title = "Statewide Concentrations of PM2.5 throughout 2002 and 2022", 
       x = "Month",
       y = "PM2.5 Concentration")

To understand how PM2.5 concentrations changed between 2002 and 2022 at the county level, I first grouped the merged data by County and year, then extracted the mean PM2.5 concentration within each county for both years. I then took the difference of the PM2.5 concentration in 2002 and 2022 for each county and plotted the difference. The plot shows that for most counties, PM2.5 concentrations decreased from 2002 to 2022, however, there were some counties, such as Trinity and Shasta, where the PM2.5 concentration increased. I found that the overall mean reduction in PM2.5 concentrations between the two years across all counties was 4.55ug/m3.

# county-level resolution
epa_county <- epa_all %>%
  group_by(year, County) %>%
  summarize(avg_conc = mean(concentration), .groups = "drop")

county_diff <- epa_county %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = year,

To understand how PM2.5 concentrations changed between 2002 and 2022 at the city level, I took a similar approach to what I did at the state level. I filtered the overall data to include only the observations in Los Angeles county. I then created boxplots to show the distribution of PM2.5 concentration in both years. The boxplots and summary stats show that there is a clear reduction in PM2.5 concentrations between 2002 and 2022, with means of 19.66um/m3 and 10.97um/m3, respectively. Like with the statewide resolution, the 2022 concentrations are more condensed than the 2002 concentrations. Within each year, I again averaged the PM2.5 concentrations for each month and plotted these in order to see whether the PM2.5 concentrations are reduced throughout the entire year of 2022, or if instead there was a month of peaked concentration. The plot shows again that the PM2.5 concentrations in 2022 were reduced throughout all 12 months compared to 2002.

epa_la_avg <- 
  epa_la %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(mdy(Date), label = F)) %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarize(avg_conc = mean(concentration), .groups = "drop")

epa_la_avg %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = month, y = avg_conc, color = year)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = month, y = avg_conc, color = year)) +
  labs(title = 
         "Los Angeles County Concentrations of PM2.5 throughout 2002 and 2022",
